ed%20the%20X-37B%20into%20a%20shuttle%20landing%20facility%20at%20NASA's%20Kennedy%20Space%20Center.%3Cp%3EMichael%20Martin%2FReleased%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EIn%201999%2C%20NASA%20selected%20Boeing%20to%20design%20a%20reusable%20orbital%20test%20vehicle%20to%20monitor%20and%20repair%20satellites%20closely.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOver%20the%20next%20four%20years%2C%20the%20X-37%20underwent%20several%20design%20iterations%20to%20achieve%20a%20more%20aerodynamic%20design%20than%20the%20Space%20Shuttle%20orbiter.%20It%20was%20initially%20intended%20to%20launch%20from%20the%20cargo%20bay%20of%20a%20space%20shuttle.%20But%20after%20the%20Space%20Shuttle%20Columbia%20crashed%20and%20killed%20all%20seven%20astronauts%20on%20board%20in%202003%2C%20it%20was%20redesigned%20to%20launch%20from%20a%20different%20rocket%2C%20making%20it%20smaller%20and%20more%20autonomous.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20project%20cost%20nearly%20%24192%20million%2C%20and%20Boeing%20was%20awarded%20another%20%24301%20million%20contract%20in%202002%20through%20the%20Space%20Launch%20Initiative%2C%20a%20joint%20research%20effort%20led%20by%20NASA%20and%20the%20Defense%20Department.%20The%20X-37%20project%20was%20transferred%20to%20the%20Defense%20Advanced%20Research%20Projects%20Agency%20in%202004%20and%20became%20classified%20because%20of%20its%20military%20applications.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%202006%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fdetails-about-air-force-space-plane-that-spent-2-years-in-space-2017-5%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ethe%20Air%20Force%3C%2Fa%3E%20announced%20the%20development%20of%20its%20own%20variant%20of%20the%20space%20plane%2C%20known%20as%20the%20X-37B%2C%20designed%20to%20operate%20with%20an%20orbital%20speed%20of%20nearly%2017%2C500%20mph%20for%20up%20to%20270%20days.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20uncrewed%20test%20vehicle%20was%20nearly%2030%20feet%20long%20and%20had%20a%20wingspan%20of%20about%2015%20feet.%20Its%20max%20takeoff%20weight